# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: age-of-sail
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby was born at Albrighton, Shropshire on 15 November 1776 to Aaron Manby of Kingston, Jamaica and Jane Lane of Bentley.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] They had a son, Charles Manby, who became Secretary of the Institution of Civil Engineers.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1807 Manby married Sarah Ann Haskins, with whom he had one daughter, Sarah Maria (d.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The oldest three of them, John Richard (1813-1869), Joseph Lane (1814-1862), and Edward Oliver (1816-1864), also became civil engineers.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's working life was originally in banks on the Isle of Wight.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1812 Manby was managing partner of the Horseley Coal and Iron Co, Tipton, Staffordshire.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] It ran coal mines, blast furnaces to make iron, and assorted workshops.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby expanded the business into civil engineering.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1813 Manby obtained patent No 3705 for a means of casting the slag from blast furnaces into blocks for building.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1815, the firm supplied a cast-iron swing bridge, possibly the first of Horseley's many iron bridges.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1821, diversifying into mechanical engineering, Manby obtained British Patent No 4558 for his "oscillating engine" designed for use in ships.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] That same year, Horseley Ironworks constructed the world's first seagoing iron steamboat, named the *Aaron Manby*, using his oscillating engine.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The boat was built at Tipton using temporary bolts, disassembled for transportation to London, and reassembled on the Thames in 1822, this time using permanent rivets.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Between 1819 and 1822, Manby started his engineering works at Charenton-le-Pont, near Paris, with the Scottish chemist Daniel Wilson as manager.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] This controversial move enabled France to stop buying engines made in England, which made Manby somewhat unpopular.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1822 Manby and Wilson's *Compagnie d'Éclairage par de Gaz Hydrogène* ('Hydrogen Gas Lighting Company') was granted the right to provide gas lighting for several streets in Paris.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] According to Michel Cotte, "The company Manby & Wilson is certainly the largest company of British origin which set up in France under the Restoration." Their *"Compagnie Anglaise"* ran until 1847, expanding to take in the Le Creusot ironworks.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's Horseley Ironworks profited from the growing canal trade, manufacturing canal bridges in the English Midlands including the Engine Arm Aqueduct (1825) and two roving bridges at Smethwick Junction (1828).
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1845 Manby sold Horseley Ironworks to John Joseph Bramah (~1798 - 1846), nephew of the inventor and locksmith Joseph Bramah.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby-ironmaster] After returning from France in about 1840, he lived at Fulham, London, before retiring to the Isle of Wight where he died.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] Launched in 1821, *Aaron Manby* was the first steamship to be built of iron.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] She was the brainchild of the eccentric but far-seeing naval officer Captain (later Admiral) Charles Napier, who had conceived the idea of a fleet of steamships for service on the River Seine.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] The ship was named after the master of the Horseley Ironworks, Tipton, Staffordshire, where she was pre-fabricated to a design jointly formulated by Captain Napier, Aaron Manby and his son Charles.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] She was then shipped in pieces to Rotherhithe on the Thames and assembled there.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] Of 116 tons burthen, the ship was 120 feet (37 m) long.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] Her flat-bottomed hull was made of 1⁄4-inch-thick (6.4 mm) iron plate fastened to angle-iron ribs.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] There was one deck, of wood, and a bowsprit.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] The ship's distinctive profile boasted a single 47-foot-high (14 m) funnel.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] The engine was of the oscillating type, designed and patented (British Patent No 4558 of 1821) by Aaron Manby.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] The paddlewheels: were 12 feet (3.7 m) in diameter but only 2.5 feet (76 cm) wide, because the vessel's maximum beam was limited to 23 feet (7.0 m) for service on the Seine.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] Defying the prevailing wisdom of the day, the iron-hulled vessel not only floated but made 9 knots (10 mph; 17 km/h) and drew one foot (30 cm) less water than any other steamboat then operating.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] After trials in May 1822, *Aaron Manby* crossed the English Channel to Le Havre under Napier's command on 10 June, at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h), carrying passengers and freighted with a cargo of linseed and iron castings.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] The ship proceeded up the Seine to Paris, where she caused a great stir and where she was based for the next decade.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] This has been claimed (incorrectly) as the first passage from Britain to France by steam ship.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] There had been shorter crossings by wooden steamers, but Napier's was the first direct steam crossing from London to Paris and the first seagoing voyage by an iron ship anywhere.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] After some further channel voyages the ship was used for pleasure trips up and down the Seine.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] The use of iron plates for the hull, in place of wood, was widely copied in shipbuilding during the following decades.
[src:age-of-sail/aaron-manby] Napier had conceived the ship as a first step towards an iron warship, and in this sense *Aaron Manby* could be considered a direct ancestor of the Royal Navy's first iron frigate, HMS *Warrior*, built the year of Napier's death.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] The game covered the naval campaigns of the French Revolutionary Wars, Napoleonic Wars and other more minor conflicts in the period 1775 to 1820.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] In addition to the campaigns there are more than 100 independent scenarios based on significant naval actions including the battles of Trafalgar and Camperdown.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] The game includes a scenario editor with over 2,000 historically accurate sailing ships allowing the extension of the game by the user.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] TalonSoft announced *Age of Sail* on July 12, 1996.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] It was initially scheduled for a fall 1996 release.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] The game received middling scores from *Computer Games Strategy Plus* and *Computer Gaming World*.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] The former publication's Robert Mayer wrote, "It should appeal greatly to fans of naval warfare, but for those gamers not inspired by stories of Trafalgar and St.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] Vincent, it might just be a bit too austere." Conversely, it received a positive review from William R.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail-video-game] In 2001, *Age of Sail* was followed by the sequel title *Age of Sail II*, developed by the Russian studio Akella.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] The **Battle of Arnemuiden** was a naval battle fought on 23 September 1338 at the start of the Hundred Years' War between England and France.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] It was the first naval battle of the Hundred Years' War and the first recorded European naval battle using artillery, as the English ship *Christopher* had three cannons and one handgun.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] The battle featured a vast French fleet under admirals Hugues Quiéret and Nicolas Béhuchet against a small squadron of five great English cogs transporting an enormous cargo of wool to Antwerp, where Edward III of England was hoping to sell it, in order to be able to pay subsidies to his allies.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] It occurred near Arnemuiden, the port of the island of Walcheren (now in the Netherlands, but then part of the County of Flanders, formally part of the Kingdom of France).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] Overwhelmed by the superior numbers and with some of their crew still on shore, John Kingston, the commander of the squadron, surrendered after a day's fighting.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] The French captured the rich cargo, took the five cogs into their fleet and massacred the English prisoners.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-arnemuiden] — Collection des chroniques nationales françaises écrites en langue vulgaire du treizième au seizième siècle, avec notes et éclaircissements par J.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The **Battle of Hampton Roads**, also referred to as the **Battle of the *Monitor* and *Merrimack*** or the **Battle of Ironclads**, was a naval battle during the American Civil War.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was fought over two days, March 8 and 9, 1862, in Hampton Roads, a roadstead in Virginia where the Elizabeth and Nansemond rivers meet the James River just before it flows into Chesapeake Bay by the city of Norfolk.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was a part of the effort of the Confederacy to break the Union blockade, which had cut off Virginia's largest cities and major industrial centers, Norfolk and Richmond, from international trade.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] This battle was significant in that it was the first combat between ironclad warships, the USS *Monitor* and CSS *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate fleet consisted of the ironclad ram *Virginia* (built from remnants of the burned steam frigate USS *Merrimack*) and several supporting vessels.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the first day of battle, they were opposed by several conventional, wooden-hulled ships of the Union Navy.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On that day, the *Virginia* was able to destroy two ships of the Union flotilla, USS *Congress* and USS *Cumberland*, and was about to attack a third, USS *Minnesota*, which had run aground.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, the action was halted by darkness and falling tide, so *Virginia* retired to take care of her few wounded—which included her captain, Flag Officer Franklin Buchanan—and repair her minimal battle damage.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Determined to complete the destruction of *Minnesota*, Catesby ap Roger Jones, acting as captain in Buchanan's absence, returned the ship to the fray the next morning, March 9.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the night, however, the ironclad *Monitor* had arrived and had taken a position to defend *Minnesota*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] When *Virginia* approached, *Monitor* intercepted her.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The two ironclads fought for about three hours, with neither able to inflict significant damage on the other.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The duel ended indecisively, *Virginia* returning to her home at the Gosport Navy Yard for repairs and strengthening, and *Monitor* to her station defending *Minnesota*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The ships did not fight again, and the blockade remained in place.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle received worldwide attention, having immediate effects on navies around the world.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The preeminent naval powers, Great Britain and France, halted further construction of wooden-hulled ships, and others followed suit.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although Britain and France had been engaged in an iron-clad arms race since the 1830s, the Battle of Hampton Roads signaled a new age of naval warfare had arrived for the whole world.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] A new type of warship, monitor, was produced on the principle of the original.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of a small number of very heavy guns, mounted so that they could fire in all directions, was first demonstrated by *Monitor* but soon became standard in warships of all types.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shipbuilders also incorporated rams into the designs of warship hulls for the rest of the century.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 19, 1861, shortly after the outbreak of hostilities at Charleston Harbor, US President Abraham Lincoln proclaimed a blockade of ports in the seceded states.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 27, after Virginia and North Carolina had also passed ordinances of secession, the blockade was extended to include their ports also.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Even before the extension, local troops had seized the Norfolk area and threatened the Gosport Navy Yard in Portsmouth.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The commandant there, Captain Charles S.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] McCauley, though loyal to the Union, was immobilized by advice he received from his subordinate officers, most of whom were in favor of secession.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although he had orders from (Union) Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles to move his ships to Northern ports, he refused to act until April 20, when he gave orders to scuttle the ships in the yard and destroy its facilities.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At least nine ships were burned, among them the screw frigate USS *Merrimack*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Merrimack* burned only to the waterline, however, and her engines were more or less intact.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The destruction of the navy yard was mostly ineffective; in particular, the large drydock there was relatively undamaged and soon could be restored.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Without firing a shot, the advocates of secession had gained for the South its largest navy yard, as well as the hull and engines of what would be in time its most famous warship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] They had also seized more than a thousand heavy guns, plus gun carriages and large quantities of gunpowder.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Norfolk and its navy yard in Portsmouth, the Confederacy controlled the southern side of Hampton Roads.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] To prevent Union warships from attacking the yard, the Confederates set up batteries at Sewell's Point and Craney Island, at the juncture of the Elizabeth River with the James.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] (See map.) The Union retained possession of Fort Monroe, at Old Point Comfort on the Virginia Peninsula.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] They also held a small man-made island known as the Rip Raps, on the far side of the channel opposite Fort Monroe, and on this island they completed another fort, named Fort Wool.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Fort Monroe went control of the lower Peninsula as far as Newport News.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Forts Monroe and Wool gave the Union forces control of the entrance to Hampton Roads.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade, initiated on April 30, 1861, cut off Norfolk and Richmond from the sea almost completely.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] To further the blockade, the Union Navy stationed some of its most powerful warships in the roadstead.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] There, they were under the shelter of the shore-based guns of Fort Monroe and the batteries at Hampton and Newport News and out of the range of the guns at Sewell's Point and Craney Island.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] For most of the first year of the war, the Confederacy could do little to oppose or dislodge them.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] When steam propulsion began to be applied to warships, naval constructors renewed their interest in armor for their vessels.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Experiments had been tried with armor during the Crimean War (1853–1856), just prior to the American Civil War, and the British and French navies had each built armored ships and were planning to build others.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1860 the French Navy commissioned *La Gloire*, the world's first ocean-going ironclad warship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Great Britain followed a year later with HMS *Warrior*, the world's first armor-plated iron-hulled warship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of armor remained controversial, however, and the United States Navy was generally reluctant to embrace the new technology.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] When the Civil War broke out in 1861, Confederate Secretary of the Navy Stephen R.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory was an early enthusiast for the advantages of armor.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As he looked upon it, the Confederacy could not match the industrial North in numbers of ships at sea, so they would have to compete by building vessels that individually outclassed those of the Union.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory gathered about himself a group of men who could put his vision into practice, among them John M.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] When Mallory's men searched the South for factories that could build engines to drive the heavy ships that he wanted, they found no place to do it immediately.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the best facility, the Tredegar Iron Works in Richmond, building engines from scratch would take at least a year.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Upon learning this, Williamson suggested taking the engines from the hulk of *Merrimack*, recently raised from the bed of the Elizabeth River.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] His colleagues promptly accepted his suggestion and expanded it, proposing that the design of their projected ironclad be adapted to the hull.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Porter produced the revised plans, which were submitted to Mallory for approval.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On July 11, 1861, the new design was accepted, and work began almost immediately.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The burned-out hull was towed into the graving dock that the Union Navy had failed to destroy.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the subsequent conversion process, the plans developed further, incorporating an iron ram fitted to the prow.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The re-modeled ship's offense, in addition to the ram, consisted of 10 guns: six 9 in (230 mm) smooth-bore Dahlgrens, two 6.4 in (160 mm) and two 7 in (180 mm) Brooke rifles.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Trials showed that these rifles firing solid shot would pierce up to eight inches of armor plating.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Tredegar Iron works could produce both solid shot and shell, and since it was believed that *Virginia* would face only wooden ships, she was given only the explosive shell.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor plating, originally meant to be 1 in (25 mm) thick, was replaced by double plates, each 2 in (51 mm) thick, backed by 24 in (61 cm) of iron and pine.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor was pierced for 14 gunports: four on each broadside, three forward, and three aft.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revisions, together with the usual problems associated with the transportation system of the South, resulted in delays that pushed out the launch date until February 3, 1862, and she was not commissioned until February 17, bearing the name CSS *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Intelligence that the Confederates were working to develop an ironclad caused consternation for the Union, but Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles waited for Congress to meet to request permission to consider building armored vessels; Congress gave this permission on August 3, 1861.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles appointed a commission, which became known as the Ironclad Board, of three senior naval officers to choose among the designs that were submitted for consideration.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The three men were Captains Joseph Smith, Hiram Paulding, and Commander Charles Henry Davis.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The board considered seventeen designs, and chose to support three.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first of the three to be completed, even though she was by far the most radical in design, was Swedish engineer and inventor John Ericsson's USS *Monitor*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson's *Monitor*, which was built at Ericsson's yard on the East River in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, incorporated new and striking design features, the most significant of which were her armor and armament.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Instead of the large numbers of guns of rather small bore that had characterized warships in the past, Ericsson opted for only two guns of large caliber; he wanted to use 15 in (380 mm) guns, but had to settle for 11 in (280 mm) Dahlgren guns when the larger size were unavailable.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] These were mounted in a cylindrical turret, 20 ft (6.1 m) in diameter, 9 ft (2.7 m) high, covered with iron 8 in (200 mm) thick.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The whole rotated on a central spindle, and was moved by a steam engine that could be controlled by one man.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson was afraid that using the full 30 pounds of black powder to fire the huge cannon would raise the risk of an explosion in the turret.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] He demanded that a charge of 15 pounds be used to lessen this possibility.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As with *Virginia*, trials found that a full charge would pierce armor plate, a finding that would have affected the outcome of the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] A serious flaw in the design was the pilot house from which the ship would be conned, a small structure forward of the turret on the main deck.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Its presence meant that the guns could not fire directly forward, and it was isolated from other activities on the ship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the late start and the novelty of construction, *Monitor* was actually completed a few days before her counterpart *Virginia*, but the Confederates activated *Virginia* first.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate chain of command was anomalous.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones had directed much of the conversion of *Merrimack* to *Virginia*, and he was disappointed when he was not named her captain.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones was retained aboard *Virginia*, but only as her executive officer.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ordinarily, the ship would have been led by a captain of the Confederate States Navy, to be determined by the rigid seniority system that was in place.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Secretary Mallory wanted the aggressive Franklin Buchanan, but at least two other captains had greater seniority and had applied for the post.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory evaded the issue by appointing Buchanan, head of the Office of Orders and Detail, flag officer in charge of the defenses of Norfolk and the James River.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As such, he could control the movements of *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Technically, therefore, the ship went into the battle without a captain.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the Union side, command of the North Atlantic Blockading Squadron was held by Flag Officer Louis M.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had devised a plan for his frigates to engage *Virginia*, hoping to trap her in their crossfire.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the event, his plan broke down completely when four of the ships ran aground (one of them intentionally) in the confined waters of the roadstead.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the day of battle, Goldsborough was absent with the ships cooperating with the Burnside Expedition in North Carolina.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In his absence, leadership fell to his second in command, Captain John Marston of USS *Roanoke*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As *Roanoke* was one of the ships that ran aground, Marston was unable to materially influence the battle, and his participation is often disregarded.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Most accounts emphasize the contribution of the captain of *Monitor*, John L.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Marston did, however, disregard orders from Secretary of War Gideon Welles to send the *Monitor* back to Washington, D.C., ahead of the battle, ensuring that it would be present to confront the *Merrimack*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle began when the large and unwieldy CSS *Virginia* steamed into Hampton Roads on the morning of March 8, 1862.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan intended to attack as soon as possible.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* was accompanied from her moorings on the Elizabeth River by *Raleigh* and *Beaufort*, and was joined at Hampton Roads by the James River Squadron, *Patrick Henry*, *Jamestown*, and *Teaser*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] When they were passing the Union batteries at Newport News, *Patrick Henry* was temporarily disabled by a shot in her boiler that killed four of her crew.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] After repairs, she returned and rejoined the others.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At this time, the Union Navy had five warships in the roadstead, in addition to several support vessels.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The sloop-of-war *Cumberland* and frigate *Congress* were anchored in the channel near Newport News.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and the steam frigates *Roanoke* and *Minnesota* were near Fort Monroe, along with the storeship *Brandywine*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The latter three got under way as soon as they saw *Virginia* approaching, but all soon ran aground.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and *Roanoke* took no further important part in the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ramming *Cumberland* nearly resulted in the sinking of *Virginia* as well.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s bow ram got stuck in the enemy ship's hull, and as *Cumberland* listed and began to go down, she almost pulled *Virginia* under with her.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the time the vessels were locked, one of *Cumberland's* anchors was hanging directly above the foredeck of *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Had it come loose, the two ships might have gone down together.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* broke free, however, her ram breaking off as she backed away.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan next turned *Virginia* on *Congress*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Seeing what had happened to *Cumberland*, Lieutenant Joseph B.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Smith, captain of *Congress*, ordered his ship grounded in shallow water.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] By this time, the James River Squadron, commanded by John Randolph Tucker, had arrived and joined *Virginia* in the attack on *Congress*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] After an hour of unequal combat, the badly damaged *Congress* surrendered.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] While the surviving crewmen of *Congress* were being ferried off the ship, a Union battery on the north shore opened fire on *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In retaliation, Buchanan ordered *Congress* fired upon with hot shot, cannonballs heated red-hot.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Congress* caught fire and burned throughout the rest of the day.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Near midnight, the flames reached her magazine and she exploded and sank, stern first.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Personnel losses included 110 killed or missing and presumed drowned.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another 26 were wounded, of whom ten died within days.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although she had not suffered anything like the damage she had inflicted, *Virginia* was not completely unscathed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shots from *Cumberland*, *Congress*, and Union troops ashore had riddled her smokestack, reducing her already low speed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her guns were disabled and several armor plates had been loosened.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her crew were killed, and more were wounded.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of the wounded was Captain Buchanan, who stood out into the open top of the *Virginia*, thinking it was perfectly safe, which led to him having his left thigh pierced by a rifle shot.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Meanwhile, the James River Squadron had turned its attention to *Minnesota*, which had left Fort Monroe to join in the battle and had run aground.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] After *Virginia* had dealt with the surrender of *Congress*, she joined the James River Squadron despite her damage.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of her deep draft and the falling tide, however, *Virginia* was unable to get close enough to be effective, and darkness prevented the rest of the squadron from aiming their guns to any effect.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* left with the expectation of returning the next day and completing the task.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She retreated into the safety of Confederate-controlled waters off Sewell's Point for the night, but had killed 250 enemy sailors and had lost two.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union had lost two ships and three were aground.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The United States Navy's greatest defeat (which would remain so until World War II) caused panic in Washington.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As Lincoln's Cabinet met to discuss the disaster, the frightened Secretary of War Edwin Stanton told the others that *Virginia* might attack East coast cities, and even shell the White House before the meeting ended.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles assured his colleagues that they were safe as the ship could not traverse the Potomac River.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] He added that the Union also had an ironclad, and that it was heading to meet *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both sides used the respite to prepare for the next day.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* put her wounded ashore and underwent temporary repairs.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan was among the wounded, so command on the second day fell to his executive officer, Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones proved to be no less aggressive than the man he replaced.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] While *Virginia* was being prepared for renewal of the battle, and while *Congress* was still ablaze, *Monitor*, commanded by Lieutenant John L.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union ironclad had been rushed to Hampton Roads in hopes of protecting the Union fleet and preventing *Virginia* from threatening Union cities.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Worden was informed that his primary task was to protect *Minnesota*, so *Monitor* took up a position near the grounded *Minnesota* and waited.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] "All on board felt we had a friend that would stand by us in our hour of trial," wrote Captain Gershom Jacques Van Brunt, *Minnesota*'s commander, in his official report the day after the engagement.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The next morning, at dawn on March 9, 1862, *Virginia* left her anchorage at Sewell's Point and moved to attack *Minnesota*, still aground.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was followed by the three ships of the James River Squadron.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] They found their course blocked, however, by the newly arrived *Monitor*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At first, Jones believed the strange craft—which one Confederate sailor mocked as "a cheese on a raft"—to be a boiler being towed from the *Minnesota*, not realizing the nature of his opponent.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Soon, however, it was apparent that he had no choice but to fight her.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first shot of the engagement was fired at *Monitor* by *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The shot flew past *Monitor* and struck *Minnesota*, which answered with a broadside; this began what would be a lengthy engagement.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] "Again, all hands were called to quarters, and when she approached within a mile of us I opened upon her with my stern guns and made a signal to the *Monitor* to attack the enemy," Van Brunt added.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] After fighting for hours, mostly at close range, neither could overcome the other.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor of both ships proved adequate.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In part, this was because each was handicapped in her offensive capabilities.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan, in *Virginia*, had not expected to fight another armored vessel, so his guns were supplied only with shell rather than armor-piercing shot.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Monitor*'s guns were used with the standard service charge of only 15 lb (6.8 kg) of powder, which did not give the projectile sufficient momentum to penetrate her opponent's armor.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Tests conducted after the battle showed that the Dahlgren guns could be operated safely and efficiently with charges of as much as 30 lb (14 kg).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, despite this, as the two ironclads circled each other during the fight, *Monitor* was about to penetrate *Virginia'*s armor, but a misfiring of her weapons caused her to lose the advantage.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At 10 AM that morning, *Virginia* grounded.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Monitor* opened fire on her vulnerable adversary, yet *Virginia* was able to scrape off the shore and rejoin the fight.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Later during the battle, Acting Master Louis N.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder and officers Stimers and Truscott were inside the gun turret, discussing the course of action.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder was leaning against the turret's inside wall when it took a direct hit.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder was knocked unconscious and taken below, where it took him an hour to regain consciousness.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder thus became the first man injured during the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle finally ceased when a shell from *Virginia* struck the pilot house of *Monitor* and exploded, driving fragments of paint and iron through the viewing slits into Worden's eyes and temporarily blinding him.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As no one else could see to command the ship, *Monitor* was forced to draw off.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The executive officer, Lieutenant Samuel Dana Greene, took over, and *Monitor* returned to the fight.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the period of command confusion, however, the crew of *Virginia* believed that their opponent had withdrawn.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although *Minnesota* was still aground, the falling tide meant that she was out of reach.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Furthermore, *Virginia* had suffered enough damage to require extensive repair.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Convinced that his ship had won the day, Jones ordered her back to Norfolk.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] At about this time, *Monitor* returned, only to discover her opponent apparently giving up the fight.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Convinced that *Virginia* was quitting, with orders only to protect *Minnesota* and not to risk his ship unnecessarily, Greene did not pursue.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Thus, each side misinterpreted the moves of the other, and as a result each claimed victory.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the two-day engagement, USS *Minnesota* shot off 78 rounds of 10-inch solid shot; 67 rounds of 10-inch shells with 15-second fuse; 169 rounds of 9-inch solid shot; 180 9-inch shells with 15-second fuse; 35 8-inch shells with 15-second fuse and 5,567.5 pounds of service powder.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Three crew members, Alexander Winslow, Henry Smith and Dennis Harrington were killed during the battle and 16 were wounded.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of *Monitor*'s crew, Quartermaster Peter Williams, was awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions during the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] By late March, the Union blockade fleet had been augmented by hastily refitted civilian ships, including the powerful SS *Vanderbilt*, SS *Arago*, SS *Illinois*, and SS *Ericsson*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] These had been outfitted with rams and some iron plating.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] By late April, the new ironclads USRC *E.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stevens* and USS *Galena* had also joined the blockade.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Each side considered how best to eliminate the threat posed by its opponent, and after *Virginia* returned each side tried to goad the other into attacking under unfavorable circumstances.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both captains declined the opportunity to fight in waters not of their own choosing; Jeffers in particular was under positive orders not to risk his ship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Consequently, each vessel spent the next month in what amounted to posturing.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because the blockade was unbroken, Norfolk was of little strategic use to the Confederacy, and preliminary plans were laid to move the ship up the James River to the vicinity of Richmond.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Before adequate preparations could be made, the Confederate Army under Major General Benjamin Huger abandoned the city on May 9, without consulting anyone from the Navy.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s draft was too great to permit her to pass up the river, which had a depth of only 18 ft (5.5 m), and then only under favorable circumstances.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was trapped and could only be captured or sunk by the Union Navy.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Rather than allow either, Tattnall decided to destroy his own ship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had her towed down to Craney Island in Portsmouth, where the gang were taken ashore, and then she was set afire.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She burned through the rest of the day and most of the following night; shortly before dawn, the flames reached her magazine, and she blew up.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The victory claims that were made by both sides in the immediate aftermath of the Battle of Hampton Roads were based on misinterpretations of the opponent's behavior and have been dismissed by present-day historians.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] They agree that the result of the *Monitor*–*Virginia* encounter was not a victory for either side.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] As the combat between ironclads was the primary significance of the battle, the general verdict is that the overall result was a draw.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] All would acknowledge that the Southern fleet inflicted far more damage than it received, which would ordinarily imply that they had gained a tactical victory.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Compared to other Civil War battles, the loss of men and ships for the Union Navy would be considered a clear defeat.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the other hand, the blockade was not seriously threatened, so the entire battle can be regarded as an assault that ultimately failed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, initially after the Battle of Hampton Roads, both the Confederate and Union media claimed victory for their own sides.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] A headline in a Boston newspaper the day after the battle read "The Merrimac Driven back by the Steamer!", implying a Union victory, while Confederate media focused on their original success against wooden Union ships.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the battle ending in a stalemate, it was seen by both sides as an opportunity to raise war-time morale, especially since the ironclad ships were an exciting naval innovation that intrigued citizens.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Evaluation of the strategic results is likewise disputed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade was maintained, even strengthened, and *Virginia* was bottled up in Hampton Roads.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because a decisive Confederate weapon was negated, some have concluded that the Union could claim a strategic victory.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Confederate advocates can counter, however, by arguing that *Virginia* had a military significance larger than the blockade, which was only a small part of the war in Tidewater Virginia.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Her mere presence was sufficient to close the James River to Federal incursions.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She also imposed other constraints on the Peninsula Campaign then being mounted by the Union Army under General George B.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] McClellan, who worried that she could interfere with his positions on the York River.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although his fears were baseless, they continued to affect the movements of his army until *Virginia* was destroyed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both days of the battle attracted attention from almost all the world's navies.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] USS *Monitor* became the prototype for the monitor warship type.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She thus became the first of two ships whose names were applied to entire classes of their successors, the other being HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Many more were built, including river monitors, and they played key roles in Civil War battles on the Mississippi and James rivers.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The US immediately started the construction of ten more monitors based on Ericsson's original larger plan, known as the *Passaic*-class monitors.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] More than 20 additional monitors were built by the Union by the end of the war.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, while the design proved exceptionally well-suited for river combat, the low profile and heavy turret caused poor seaworthiness in rough waters.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Russia, fearing that the American Civil War would spill into Russian Alaska, launched ten sister ships, as soon as Ericsson's plans reached St.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] What followed has been described as *"Monitor mania"*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revolving turret later inspired similar designs for future warships, which eventually became the modern battleship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The vulnerability of wooden hulls to armored ships was noted particularly in Britain and France, where the wisdom of the planned conversion of the battle fleet to armor was given a powerful demonstration.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another feature that was emulated was not so successful.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Impressed by the ease with which *Virginia* had sunk *Cumberland*, naval architects began to incorporate rams into their hull designs.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first purpose-built ram in the modern era was the French armored ram *Taureau*, whose guns were said to have "the sole function of preparing the way for the ram." The inclusion of rams in warship hull design persisted almost to the outbreak of World War I.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The name of the warship that served the Confederacy in the Battle of Hampton Roads has been a continuing source of confusion and some contention.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was originally a screw frigate in the United States Navy carrying the name USS *Merrimack*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] All parties continued to use the name after her capture by secessionists while she was being rebuilt as an ironclad.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] When her conversion was almost complete, her name was officially changed to *Virginia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the official name change, Union accounts persisted in calling *Merrimack* by her original name, while Confederate sources used either *Virginia* or *Merrimac(k)*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The alliteration of *Monitor* and *Merrimack* has persuaded most popular accounts to adopt the familiar name, even when it is acknowledged to be technically incorrect.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was a paddle wheel steamer named for the victor (as most Southerners saw it) at Hampton Roads.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was used for running the blockade until she was captured and taken into Federal service, still named *Merrimac.* Her name was a spelling variant of the river, namesake of USS *Merrimack*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both spellings are still in use around the Hampton Roads area.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] A small community in Montgomery County, Virginia, near the location where the iron for the Confederate ironclad was forged is now known as Merrimac.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Some of the iron mined there and used in the plating on the Confederate ironclad is displayed at the Norfolk Naval Shipyard in Portsmouth.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The anchor of *Virginia* sits on the lawn in front of the American Civil War Museum in Richmond.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] After resting undetected on the ocean floor for 111 years, the wreck of *Monitor* was located by a team of scientists in 1973.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The remains of the ship were found upside down 16 mi (26 km) off Cape Hatteras, on a relatively flat, sandy bottom at a depth of about 240 ft (73 m).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1987, the site was declared a National Marine Sanctuary, the first shipwreck to receive this distinction.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of *Monitor*'s advanced state of deterioration, timely recovery of remaining significant artifacts and ship components became critical.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Numerous fragile artifacts, including the innovative turret and its two Dahlgren guns, an anchor, steam engine, and propeller, have been recovered.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] They were transported back to Hampton Roads to the Mariners' Museum in Newport News, Virginia, where they were treated in special tanks to stabilize the metal.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] It was reported that it would take about ten years for the metal to completely stabilize.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The new USS *Monitor* Center at the Mariners' Museum officially opened on March 9, 2007, and a full-scale copy of USS *Monitor*, the original recovered turret, and artifacts and related items are now on display.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Battle of Hampton Roads was a significant event in both Naval and Civil War history that has been detailed in many books, televised Civil War documentaries, and in film, to include TNT's 1991 *Ironclads*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In New York City, where the designer of the Monitor, John Ericsson, died in March 1889, a statue was commissioned by the state to commemorate the battle between the Ironclads.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The statue features a stylized male nude allegorical figure on water between two iron cleats.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] In Virginia, the state dedicated the Monitor-Merrimack Overlook at Anderson Park on a jetty that overlooks the site of the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] The park contains several historical markers commemorating both ships.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-hampton-roads] Also, in 1992, Virginia dedicated the $400 million, 4.6-mile-long Monitor-Merrimac Memorial Bridge-Tunnel, which is located less than 1 mile from the site of the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Ottoman forces were sailing westward from their naval station in Lepanto (the Venetian name of ancient Naupactus – Greek Ναύπακτος, Turkish *İnebahtı*) when they met the fleet of the Holy League which was sailing east from Messina, Sicily.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Lepanto marks the last major engagement in the Western world to be fought almost entirely between rowing vessels, namely the galleys and galleasses, which were the direct descendants of ancient trireme warships.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The battle was in essence an "infantry battle on floating platforms".
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It was the largest naval battle in Western history since classical antiquity, involving more than 450 warships.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Over the following decades, the increasing importance of the galleon and the line of battle tactic would displace the galley as the major warship of its era, marking the beginning of the "Age of Sail".
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The victory of the Holy League is of great importance in the history of Europe and of the Ottoman Empire, with the Ottoman fleet almost completely destroyed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] However, the battle had no lasting impact on the Ottoman navy as the Ottomans rapidly rebuilt their fleet in under 6 months.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The battle has long been compared to the Battle of Salamis, both for tactical parallels and for its crucial importance in the defense of Europe against imperial expansion.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It was also of great symbolic importance in a period when Europe was torn by its own wars of religion following the Protestant Reformation.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Pope Pius V instituted the feast of Our Lady of Victory, and Philip II of Spain used the victory to strengthen his position as the "Most Catholic King" and defender of Christendom against Muslim incursion.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christian coalition had been promoted by Pope Pius V to rescue the Venetian colony of Famagusta on the island of Cyprus, which was being besieged by the Turks in early 1571 subsequent to the fall of Nicosia and other Venetian possessions in Cyprus in the course of 1570.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] On 1 August the Venetians surrendered after being reassured that they could leave Cyprus freely.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] However, the Ottoman commander, Lala Kara Mustafa Pasha, had lost some 50,000 men in the siege and broke his word, imprisoning the Venetians, and had Marco Antonio Bragadin flayed alive.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The banner for the fleet, blessed by the Pope, reached the Kingdom of Naples (then ruled by Philip II of Spain) on 14 August 1571, where it was solemnly consigned to John of Austria.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] All members of the alliance viewed the Ottoman navy as a significant threat, both to the security of maritime trade in the Mediterranean Sea and to the security of continental Europe itself.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Spain was the largest financial contributor, though the Spaniards preferred to preserve most of their galleys for Spain's own wars against the nearby sultanates of the Barbary Coast rather than expend its naval strength for the benefit of Venice.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The combined Christian fleet was placed under the command of John of Austria with Marcantonio Colonna as his principal deputy.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The various Christian contingents met the main force from Venice under Sebastiano Venier, later Doge of Venice, in July and August 1571 at Messina, Sicily.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christian fleet consisted of 206 galleys and six galleasses (large new galleys with masts and sails in addition to their oars, and substantial artillery, developed by the Venetians).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The reserve, meant to reinforce any necessary point of the line, was commanded by the Spanish Álvaro de Bazán.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Aside from the galleys and galleasses, the fleet included a division of galleons, composed by 24 from Spain and two Venetians.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Not being rowing ships, they moved as an independent squad and were left out of the battle under the command of Cesare d'Avalos.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] There was also a squad of 76 galiots and fustas, including 50 from Spain, 20 from Venice and six from the Papal States, which would act as auxiliaries and messengers for the main fleet.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] This fleet of the Christian alliance was manned by 40,000 sailors and oarsmen.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] A significant number of Greeks also participated in the conflict on the side of the Holy League with three Venetian galleys commanded by Greek captains.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The historian George Finlay estimated that over 25,000 Greeks fought on the side of the Holy League during the battle (both as soldiers and sailors/oarsmen) and stated that their numbers "far exceeded that of the combatants of any other nation engaged".
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Oarsmen were mainly drawn from local Greek populations, who were experienced in maritime affairs, although there were some Venetian oarsmen as well.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Free oarsmen were generally acknowledged to be superior to enslaved or imprisoned oarsmen, but the former were gradually replaced in all galley fleets (including those of Venice from 1549) during the 16th century by cheaper slaves, convicts, and prisoners-of-war owing to rapidly rising costs.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Venetian oarsmen were mainly free citizens and able to bear arms, adding to the fighting power of their ships, whereas convicts were used to row many of the galleys in other Holy League squadrons.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] A heavy effort was done from the beginning to learn by past mistakes of the previous Holy League in the 1538 Battle of Preveza, where a similar alliance had been routed by an inferior Ottoman fleet.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The new battle plan was heavily influenced by Viceroy of Sicily Garcia de Toledo, experienced in the Ottoman-Habsburg naval wars, who advised John of Austria that the fleet should adopt the battle plan used by the Ottomans themselves in Preveza.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In order to prevent the infighting, John of Austria further ordered the fleet would not sail divided in national blocks as in Preveza, but in squads with galleys of all their nationalities intermixed, with the experienced Spanish and Italian infantry embarked in all of the vessels.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] He also arranged for the fleet to sail from Messina already in formation and maintain it up to the battle to earn cohesion and rowing experience.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Gianandrea Doria also advised to saw off the long bow of the galleys so they could fire more easily their main guns at close range.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Ali Pasha, the Ottoman admiral (*Kapudan-i Derya*), supported by the corsairs Mehmed Sirocco (Mehmed Şuluk) of Alexandria and Uluç Ali, commanded an Ottoman force of 222 war galleys, 56 galliots, and some smaller vessels.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Turks had skilled and experienced crews of sailors but were significantly deficient in their elite corps of janissaries.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The number of oarsmen was about 37,000, virtually all of them slaves, many of them Christians who had been captured in previous conquests and engagements.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Ali Pasha is supposed to have told his Christian galley slaves, "If I win the battle, I promise you your liberty.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] While soldiers on board the ships were roughly matched in numbers, an advantage for the Christians was the numerical superiority in guns and cannon aboard their ships.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It is estimated that the Christians had 1,815 guns, while the Turks had only 750 with insufficient ammunition.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christians embarked with their much improved arquebusier and musketeer forces, while the Ottomans trusted in their greatly feared composite bowmen.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Another differential factor was the Spanish experience at using marine infantry, adept at boarding enemy ships and fighting on their decks, even using pikes.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christian fleet started from Messina on 16 September, crossing the Adriatic and creeping along the coast, arriving at the group of rocky islets lying just north of the opening of the Gulf of Corinth on 6 October.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Serious conflict had broken out between Venetian and Spanish soldiers, and Venier enraged John of Austria by hanging a Spanish soldier for impudence.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Despite bad weather, the Christian ships sailed south and, on 6 October, reached the port of Sami, Cephalonia (then also called Val d'Alessandria), where they remained for a while.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Early on 7 October, they sailed toward the Gulf of Patras, where they encountered the Ottoman fleet.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] While neither fleet had immediate strategic resources or objectives in the gulf, both chose to engage.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Ottoman fleet had an express order from Selim II to fight, and John of Austria found it necessary to attack in order to maintain the integrity of the expedition in the face of personal and political disagreements within the Holy League.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The lookout on the *Real* sighted the Turkish van at dawn of 7 October.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] John of Austria called a council of war and decided to offer battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] He travelled through his fleet in a swift sailing vessel, exhorting his officers and men to do their utmost.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Sacrament was administered to all, the galley slaves were freed from their chains, and the standard of the Holy League was raised to the truck of the flagship.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] John of Austria, named overall commander of the fleet by Pope Pius V, led the centre division along with Papal captain Marcantonio Colonna and the Venetian Sebastiano Venier; the wings were commanded by the Venetian Agostino Barbarigo and the Genoese Gianandrea Doria.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Ottoman fleet consisted of 222 galleys and 56 galliots and was led by Müezzinzade Ali Pasha, Mahomet Sirocco and Occhiali.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The wind was at first against the Christians, and it was feared that the Turks would be able to make contact before a line of battle could be formed.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] But around noon, shortly before contact, the wind shifted to favour the Christians, enabling most of the squadrons to reach their assigned position before contact.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Four galeasses stationed in front of the Christian battle line opened fire at close quarters at the foremost Turkish galleys, confusing their battle array in the crucial moment of contact.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Around noon, first contact was made between the squadrons of Barbarigo and Sirocco, close to the northern shore of the Gulf.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Barbarigo had attempted to stay so close to the shore as to prevent Sirocco from surrounding him, but Sirocco, knowing the depth of the waters, managed to still insert galleys between Barbarigo's line and the coast.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In the ensuing mêlée, the ships came so close to each other as to form an almost continuous platform of hand-to-hand fighting.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Barbarigo was killed by an arrow to the eye, but the timely arrival of Bazán with the reserve fleet balanced the situation, with Sirocco being eventually killed and beheaded.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christian galley slaves freed from the Turkish ships were supplied with arms and joined in the fighting, turning the battle in favour of the Christian side.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Meanwhile, the centres clashed with such force that Ali Pasha's galley drove into the *Real* as far as the fourth rowing bench, and hand-to-hand fighting commenced around the two flagships, between the Spanish Tercio infantry and the Turkish janissaries.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] When the *Real* was nearly taken, Colonna came alongside, with the bow of his galley, and mounted a counter-attack.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] With the help of Colonna, the Turks were pushed off the *Real* and the Turkish flagship was boarded and swept.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The flagship's entire crew was killed, including Ali Pasha himself.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The banner of the Holy League was hoisted on the captured ship, breaking the morale of the Turkish galleys nearby.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] After two hours of fighting, the Turks were beaten left and centre, although fighting continued for another two hours.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] A flag taken at Lepanto by the Knights of Saint Stephen, said to be the standard of the Turkish commander, is still on display at Santo Stefano dei Cavalieri church, the seat of the Order in Pisa.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] On the Christian right, the situation was different, as Doria continued sailing towards the south instead of taking his assigned position.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] He would explain his conduct after the battle by saying that he was trying to prevent an enveloping manoeuvre by the Turkish left.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] But Doria's captains were enraged, interpreting their commander's signals as a sign of treachery.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] When Doria had opened a wide gap with the Christian centre, Uluç Ali swung around and fell on Colonna's southern flank, with Doria too far away to interfere.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Ali attacked a group of some fifteen galleys around the flagship of the Knights of Malta, threatening to break into the Christian centre and still turn the tide of the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] This was prevented again by the arrival of the reserve squadron commanded by Bazán.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Uluç Ali was forced to retreat, escaping the battle with the captured flag of the Knights of Malta.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Isolated fighting continued until the evening.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Even after the battle had clearly turned against the Turks, groups of janissaries kept fighting to the last.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It is said that at some point the Janissaries ran out of weapons and started throwing oranges and lemons at their Christian adversaries, leading to awkward scenes of laughter among the general misery of battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Many Greek rowers serving on Turkish galleys managed to seize them with mutiny and deliver them in time to the Christian allies.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] At the end of the battle, the Christians had captured 117 galleys and sunk or destroyed some 83 other.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Around ten thousand Turks were taken prisoner, and many thousands of Christian slaves were rescued.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christian side suffered around 7,500 deaths, the Turkish side about 30,000.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Other sources place the losses higher, with 10,000 Christians and 40,000 Ottomans dead.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The engagement was a significant defeat for the Ottomans, who had not lost a major naval battle since the fifteenth century.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] However, the Holy League failed to capitalize on the victory, and while the Ottoman defeat has often been cited as the historical turning-point initiating the eventual stagnation of Ottoman territorial expansion, this was by no means an immediate consequence.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Christian victory at Lepanto confirmed the *de facto* division of the Mediterranean, with the eastern half under firm Ottoman control and the western under the Spanish Crown and their Italian allies.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The battle halted the Ottoman encroachment on Italian territories, but the Holy League did not regain any territories that had been lost to the Ottomans prior to Lepanto.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Ottomans were quick to rebuild their navy.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] By 1572, about six months after the defeat, more than 150 galleys, 8 galleasses, and in total 250 ships had been built, including eight of the largest capital ships ever seen in the Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] With this new fleet the Ottoman Empire was able to reassert its supremacy in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In 1572, the allied Christian fleet resumed operations and faced a renewed Ottoman navy of 200 vessels under Kılıç Ali Pasha, but the Ottoman commander actively avoided engaging the allied fleet and headed for the safety of the fortress of Modon.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The arrival of the Spanish squadron of 55 ships evened the numbers on both sides and opened the opportunity for a decisive blow, but friction among the Christian leaders and the reluctance of John of Austria squandered the opportunity and the subsequent attack was abandoned.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The diverging interests of the League members began to show, and the alliance began to unravel.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In 1573, the Holy League fleet failed to sail altogether; instead, John of Austria attacked and took Tunis, only for it to be retaken by the Ottomans in 1574.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Venice, fearing the loss of its Dalmatian possessions and a possible invasion of Friuli, and eager to cut its losses and resume the trade with the Ottoman Empire, initiated unilateral negotiations with the Porte.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Holy League was disbanded with the peace treaty of 7 March 1573, which concluded the War of Cyprus.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Venice was forced to accept loser's terms in spite of the victory at Lepanto.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Cyprus was formally ceded to the Ottoman Empire, and Venice agreed to pay an indemnity of 300,000 ducats.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In addition, the border between the two powers in Dalmatia was modified by the Turkish occupation of small but important parts of the hinterland that included the most fertile agricultural areas near the cities, with adverse effects on the economy of the Venetian cities in the region.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Peace would hold between the two states until the Cretan War of 1645.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In 1574, the Ottomans retook the strategic city of Tunis from the Spanish-supported Hafsid dynasty, which had been re-installed after John of Austria's forces reconquered the city from the Ottomans the year before.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Thanks to the long-standing Franco-Ottoman alliance, the Ottomans were able to resume naval activity in the western Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In 1576, the Ottomans assisted in Abdul Malik's capture of Fez – this reinforced the Ottoman indirect conquests in Morocco that had begun under Suleiman the Magnificent.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The establishment of Ottoman suzerainty over the area placed the entire southern coast of the Mediterranean from the Straits of Gibraltar to Greece under Ottoman authority, with the exceptions of the Spanish-controlled trading city of Oran and strategic settlements such as Melilla and Ceuta.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] But after 1580, the Ottoman Empire could no longer compete with the advances of European navies, especially following the development of the galleon and the posterior line of battle tactics.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] This would be first demonstrated in the battle of Cape Gelidonya in 1616, regarded as a "little Lepanto", where six Spanish sailing ships under Francisco de Ribera defeated 55 Ottoman galleys.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The Holy League credited the victory to the Virgin Mary, whose intercession with God they had implored for victory through the use of the Rosary.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Andrea Doria had kept a copy of the miraculous image of Our Lady of Guadalupe given to him by King Philip II of Spain in his ship's state room.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Pope Pius V instituted a new Catholic feast day of Our Lady of Victory to commemorate the battle, which is now celebrated by the Catholic Church as the feast of Our Lady of the Rosary.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Dominican friar Juan Lopez in his 1584 book on the rosary states that the feast of the rosary was offered "in memory and in perpetual gratitude of the miraculous victory that the Lord gave to his Christian people that day against the Turkish armada".
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] A piece of commemorative music composed after the victory is the motet *Canticum Moysis* (Song of Moses Exodus 15) *Pro victoria navali contra Turcas* by the Spanish composer based in Rome Fernando de las Infantas.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The other piece of music is Jacobus de Kerle's "Cantio octo vocum de sacro foedere contra Turcas" 1572 (Song in Eight Voices on the Holy League Against the Turks), in the opinion of Pettitt (2006) an "exuberantly militaristic" piece celebrating the victory.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] There were celebrations and festivities with *triumphs* and pageants at Rome and Venice with Turkish slaves in chains.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Giovanni Pietro Contarini's *History of the Events, which occurred from the Beginning of the War Brought against the Venetians by Selim the Ottoman, to the Day of the Great and Victorious Battle against the Turks* was published in 1572, a few months after Lepanto.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It was the first comprehensive account of the war, and the only one to attempt a concise but complete overview of its course and the Holy League's triumph.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Contarini's account went beyond effusive praise and mere factual reporting to examine the meaning and importance of these events.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It is also the only full historical account by an immediate commentator, blending his straightforward narrative with keen and consistent reflections on the political philosophy of conflict in the context of the Ottoman–Catholic confrontation in the early modern Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] There are many pictorial representations of the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Prints of the order of battle appeared in Venice and Rome in 1571.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Numerous paintings were commissioned, including one in the Doge's Palace, Venice, by Andrea Vicentino on the walls of the *Sala dello Scrutinio*, which replaced Tintoretto's *Victory of Lepanto*, destroyed by fire in 1577.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Titian painted the battle in the background of an allegorical work showing Philip II of Spain holding his infant son, Don Fernando, his male heir born shortly after the victory, on 4 December 1571.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] An angel descends from heaven bearing a palm branch with a motto for Fernando, who is held up by Philip: "Majora tibi" (may you achieve greater deeds; Fernando died as a child, in 1578).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] A painting by Wenceslas Cobergher, dated to the end of the 16th century, now in San Domenico Maggiore, shows what is interpreted as a victory procession in Rome on the return of admiral Colonna.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] On the stairs of Saint Peter's Basilica, Pius V is visible in front of a kneeling figure, identified as Marcantonio Colonna returning the standard of the Holy League to the pope.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] On high is the Madonna and child with victory palms.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Tommaso Dolabella painted his *The Battle of Lepanto* in c.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] 1625–1630 on the commission of Stanisław Lubomirski, commander of the Polish left wing in the Battle of Khotyn (1621).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The monumental painting (3.05 m × 6.35 m) combines the Polish victory procession following this battle with the backdrop of the Battle of Lepanto.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It was later owned by the Dominicans of Poznań and since 1927 has been on display in Wawel Castle, Kraków.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The statue of John of Austria in Messina was erected by decision of the city's Senate in 1571, as John had returned to Messina after the battle.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] It was sculpted by Andrea Calamech and dedicated in 1572.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] There was an immediate poetical response to the victory at Lepanto.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In Italy alone 233 titles of sonnets, madrigals and poems were printed between 1571 and 1573, some of these including writing in dialect or Latin.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] This was replicated by the Spanish response, with poems in Catalan and the Mallorcan dialect and full scale epics by Juan Latino (*Austriados libri duo* 1573), Jerónimo Corte-Real ( *Austriada ou Felicissima Victoria*, 1578) and es:Juan Rufo (*La Austriada*, 1586).
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Though these longer works have, in the words of a later critic, "not unjustly been consigned to that oblivion which few epics have escaped", there was also a Spanish ballad which retained its popularity and was translated into English by Thomas Rodd in 1818.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The most popular British poem on the subject was *The Lepanto* by King James VI of Scotland.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Written in fourteeners about 1585, its thousand lines were ultimately collected in *His Maiesties Poeticall Exercises at Vacant Houres* (1591), then published separately in 1603 after James had become king of England too.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] The royal connection ensured that the battle was featured in Stuart aquatic pageants representing sea battles between Christians and Turks well into the reign.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In 1632, the story of the battle was retold in couplets in Abraham Holland's *Naumachia*.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Chesterton revisited the conflict in his lively narrative poem *Lepanto*, first published in 1911 and republished many times since.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] At the start of the 20th century too, Emilio Salgari devoted his historical novel, *Il Leone di Damasco* ("The Lion of Damascus", 1910), to the Battle of Lepanto, which was eventually to be adapted to film by Corrado D'Errico in 1942.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] In 1942 as well, English author Elizabeth Goudge has a character in her war-time novel, *The Castle on the Hill* (1942), recall the leading role of John of Austria in the battle and the presence of Cervantes there.
[src:age-of-sail/battle-of-lepanto-1571] Much as combatants had appropriated Chesterton's poem to the circumstances of World War I, Goudge harnessed that ancient incident to British resistance to Nazi Germany during World War II.
